{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1bc807e7-e340-4039-a72c-fd2d7f0dd5b3","content":"In .NET 10 MAUI, the iOS-specific `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with a **cross-platform** `SafeAreaRegions` property directly on `Page`.\n\n**Before (.NET 9):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"\n    ...>\n```\n\n**After (.NET 10):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    SafeAreaRegions=\"All\"\n    ...>\n```\n\nYou can drop the `xmlns:ios` declaration entirely if it was only used for safe area. The `SafeAreaRegions` enum also supports granular control: `None`, `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, `Right`, or combinations like `Top,Bottom`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"07199948-f749-4b5a-8db4-d88f16901a36","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI migration issue from .NET 9 to .NET 10 regarding safe area handling on iOS. This is a known breaking change in .NET 10 MAUI.\n\nIn .NET 10, the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` attached property was removed/deprecated. The replacement is to use the new `SafeAreaRegions` property on `Page` (or individual layout controls).\n\nLet me provide the correct answer based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI .NET 10 changes.\n\nIn .NET 10 MAUI, `Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with a cross-platform `Page.SafeAreaRegions` property. \n\nThe `SafeAreaRegions` enum offers values like `None`, `All`, `Left`, `Right`, `Top`, and `Bottom` to control which edges respect the safe area. Instead of using the iOS-specific namespace with `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`, you now set `SafeAreaRegions` directly on the `Page` element as a cross-platform property.","outputTokens":539,"requestId":"B7D3:396FF8:17B28E:1F2303:69FFDA8E"},"id":"48ec51ed-d030-4986-98d4-56beba5a3945","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:08:42.041Z","parentId":"bc9b79f7-544e-4357-bc14-e93bc3515d88"}
